Travel Tips

Top Apps to download to make your travels stress free.

You can navigate Australia using these apps:

TripGo- Great for displaying the train platforms etc when changing trains and up to date bus routes you can track the current location of the next bus.

Waze- Useful if you are driving as it highlights Toll routes and also speed cameras and up to date traffic alerts.

Uber- Cheap rides around the City.

Download the below apps for great deals for food and drinks:

Eat Club- regularly updated discounts, you can use the map to find up to 50% discounts near you. You just need to book a table using the app and show the code on arrival. (You can book last minute)

The Happiest Hour- Shows nearby happy hour deals as well as food discounts.

For accommodation options download the below apps:

Booking.com- All types of hotels can be found on booking.com, they often offer free cancellation so this will help you plan ahead but still gives you flexibility.

HostelWorld- Great for booking last minute hostels and they are rated based on a young audiences experience.

WikiCamps- Shows all the available camp grounds in Australia, it is also available offline which means its accessible when exploring a little further off the grid.

Additional Apps that we recommend:

Beach safe- An app that tells you if the beach is safe to swim and where to find the flags that are safe to swim between. This is very important in Australia as the tide can be extremely strong and there are also potentially dangerous saline in unsupervised waters.

XE Currency Converter- The most up to date way to check the conversion rate which will help you manage your spending.

Nature Near Me- Great for finding local hikes and seeing what amenities that are available at each spot as well as total distance and pictures on the route.

WikiCamps- Shows all the available camp grounds in Australia, it is also available offline which means its accessible when exploring a little further off the grid.

Introduction to: Sydney

Intro to Sydney

Sydney is one of the largest Cities in Australia and it is known for its iconic landmarks, such as the Sydney Harbour Bridge and the Sydney Opera House.

Sydney offers the perfect balance of beach life and city life, with some of Australia's most famous beaches being just a 15minute drive from the City.

Aside from the tourist hotspots Sydney also offers lots of other activities such as bottomless brunches or hikes in the National park.

If you're looking for a relaxing day and a vibrant nightlife Sydney has it all.

Getting Around

If you are flying in to Sydney airport you can catch the train from both the International and domestic airport straight to Central station or Circular Quay, you can use your contactless bank card to tap on and off, prices start from $17.39. Using a contactless bank card is cheaper than purchasing a ticket. However if you are travelling with others it may be cheaper to book an Uber.

You can purchase an Opal Card to benefit from reduced fares. The initial ‘purchase’ is $10 but you will have $10 of credit so the card is essentially free. You can purchase a card from WH Smiths if you arrive from the International airport or alternatively you can search here for the nearest purchase point. https://transportnsw.info/opal-retailers#/ The cards can be topped up at stations or using the mobile app.

Travelling on a Sunday is usually capped at $3 when using an opal card which means it is the best day for catching the Ferry’s as they are normally far more expensive. If you are spending a few days in Sydney once you have reached 8 journeys on your opal card your journeys for the rest of the week are significantly reduced.

Travel around the City is really reasonably priced (much cheaper than travelling from the airport station which carries higher fee’s) for example Central to Circular Quay or Bondi Junction can be as little as $2.50.

Introduction to: Melbourne

Intro to Melbourne

Melbourne is a vibrant City in the South of Australia. It is known for being an artistic city with lots of beautiful graffiti laneways, quirky cafe's and rooftop bars.

Melbourne is surrounded by some great locations that are ideal for day trips. A few examples are Philip Islands to see the Penguins or maybe a trip to the Yarra Valley wine region.

Getting Around

If you are flying in to Melbourne you should book your flight to arrive at Tullamarine Airport. From here you can head to the SkyBus area outside of the terminal where you can get a bus in to the City for $19. When buying a ticket you will need to tell the service desk where your accommodation is or where you are heading and they will advise you which bus is best for you.

You can purchase a Myki Card to benefit from reduced fares. The initial ‘purchase’ is $30 but you will have $24 of credit so the card is $6. You can purchase a card from most 7-Eleven’s or from Myki Machines at selected stations. You can search for the nearest purchase point here https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/footer/customer-service/staffed-stations/ The cards can be topped up at stations or using the mobile app if you have an Android phone.

Melbourne also has a free tram zone from Queen Victoria Market to Docklands, Spring Street, Flinders Street Station and Federation Square. The City Circle Tram is also free. More information about fares can be found at https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/travelling-on-the-network/visiting-melbourne-and-victoria/

Introduction to: Brisbane

Intro to Brisbane

Brisbane is best known for being the Capital of Queensland. Brisbane has museums, science centres and art galleries, as well as botanical gardens and a man made beach on the South Bank. Brisbane offers something for everyone, a little bit of City between the coastal towns along the East Coast.

Getting Around

If you are flying in to Brisbane you will be able to catch the train direct to Central station as well as many other locations across the City. The Airtrain runs roughly every 15 minutes (could be longer during off peak) and fares start from $15 to get to Central station. You can calculate the price of your journey here. https://translink.com.au/tickets-and-fares/fares-and-zones

If you are going to be using public transport when travelling between the Gold Coast and the Sunshine Coast you will need a GoCard. You can purchase a GoCard from Brisbane Airport train station or from other outlets such as 7-Eleven. More options can be found here. https://translink.com.au/tickets-and-fares/go-card/locations. GoCards cost $10 and will need a minimum $10 at the time of purchase. You cannot use a bank card to tap on or off so you should purchase a Go Card as individual tickets are a lot more expensive if you plan to use lots of transport this will become costly.

The City Hopper is a free cruise service that runs every 36 minutes to New Farm and back to North Quay.

Intro to The Gold Coast

The Gold Coast is known for its long stretches of beaches and it's high profile suburbs including Burleigh Heads. The Gold Coast has a wildlife centre that allows you to get up close with the Australian animals as well as Internationally known theme parks.

Introduction to: Byron

Intro to Byron

Byron Bay is the hippie hotspot of the East Coast of Australia and it has loads to offer including, surfing, hidden beaches, boutique shops with beautiful clothes and a care free vibe.

Expect to have adventurous days with chilled evenings listening to the local buskers.

Getting Around

If you are looking to get to Byron from the Coolangatta Airport the Skybus operates every 2 hours with a one way trip at just $28 for the 55minute journey which is much cheaper than any of the taxi's available. It's worth checking the timetable in advance as you may find yourself just missing a shuttle and having to wait 2 hours. Sky Bus

Byron doesn’t have any other form of public transport once you are in town however everything is easily accessible on foot or by taxi.

Introduction to: Canberra

Intro to Canberra

Canberra is Australia's largest inland city and the eighth-largest city overall. Located between Australia's 2 largest cities, Melbourne and Sydney.

Canberra is the capital city of Australia and is home to the nations Parliament house.

Getting Around

After arriving at Canberra airport you can head straight for the Airport bus station to catch a bus in to the City. Buses can vary from 30-45 minutes depending on the route. However if you are happy to pay a little more, especially if travelling in a group you can get a taxi for the roughly 10 minute journey.

Canberra has buses and light rail trains that cover the majority of the City making it really easy to get around. You can either purchase a MyWay Card for $20 with $20 worth of credit or pay by cash for each of your journeys. Purchasing a MyWay Card saves you roughly $1.30 per journey however this may not be worth it if you are not in Canberra for long as when purchasing a cash ticket for $5 it last for 90 minutes which may work out more cost effective than purchasing the MyWay Card for $20.

If you don’t carry cash you must purchase a MyWay card.

Introduction to: Adelaide

Intro to Adelaide

Adelaide is South Australia's Coastal Capital. Adelaide offers the Barossa Valley wine region, Kangaroo Island and some of the biggest festivals in Australia.

Getting Around

If you’re arriving in to Adelaide airport you can take either the JetExpress direct in to the City or the JetBus for Glenelg, West Beach and the City, servicing all routes. You will need a MetroCard which can be purchased from the airport ticket vending machine near the bus stop.

Purchasing a MetroCard for $5 can save you just under $2 per journey you take on buses, even if your only staying for a short period of time it could save you a little bit of money, and as a backpacker you know that a little good deed from a stranger goes a long way, so why not pass the card on to another traveller when you leave.

Adelaide also has a free Tram service through the City from North Terraces to South Terraces which means accessing Adelaide Central Markets, Adelaide Zoo and the Botanical Gardens really easy. More information about the routes can be found at https://www.cityofadelaide.com.au/transport-parking/public-transport/trains-trams-buses/

Introduction to: Fraser Island

Intro to Fraser Island

Fraser Island is the world's largest sand island, stretching over 120km and is one of only 20 in the world. Fraser Island is an adventure playground with it's impressive natural beauty. It's a camping and ecotourism destination, with beaches and swimming sites at Lake McKenzie, Lake Wabby and other freshwater pools.

Getting Around

Fraser Island doesn’t have any form of transport so you can either opt for a guided tour where you can either self drive or be driven a a tour coach specifically designed for the roads on Fraser Island. The Island is completely made from sand so you need to make sure you have a suitable car if you chose to hire a car and tour the Island yourself. Many cars get stuck on the Island every year so make sure your hire car has suitable wheels or join a tour group.

Introduction to: Airlie Beach

Intro to Airlie Beach

Airlie Beach is the vibrant hub of the Whitsundays and the ideal mainland base for fun and adventure in the Whitsundays. Located on the Great Barrier Reef and known for it's young and adventurous atmosphere it is the perfect launching pad for activities on the water and in the lush, green rainforest of the Whitsunday Coast. If you're looking to explore the Whitsunday Islands without the expense of staying on the Islands then this is definitely the place for you.

Getting Around

If you have flown in to Proserpine Airport you will find plenty of shuttle buses that can transport you to Airlie Beach. Many of these need to be rebooked so it’s recommended to book a shuttle before your flight. You can book a one way pick up for $20 or a $34 return with Airlie Beach Transfers

Whitsundays Transit is the local bus service connecting Proserpine, Cannonvale, Airlie Beach and Shute Harbour. Airlie beach is a small town where everything is accessible on foot. However some accommodation are located on fairly steep hills and if you don’t fancy walking there are plenty of cheap taxis in the area that will cost no more the $12 to get you across town.

Introduction to: Cairns

Intro to Cairns

Cairns is located in far North Queensland and is right at the heart of the Great Barrier Reef. Cairns is known for activities such as diving, white water rafting and bungy jumping, along with a great nightlife.

Cape Tribulation is a short day trip from Cairns and it is the only place in the world where the Reef meets the Rainforest.

Getting Around

Cairns has very limited transport options so you will need to book a taxi or an Uber from the airport.

Most tourist locations are within walking distance or may require using taxi services.

DAY 1 : Kangaroo island

View Image

DAY 1

Location: Adelaide

Activity: Kangaroo island

Kangaroo Island is just off the peninsula from Cape Jervis which is roughly an hour and 40 minutes from Adelaide CBD. The transport from Adelaide CBD to Cape Jervis is limited so you will need to either drive or book the Sealink coach service. The most recent timetable can be found at Public coach timetable Tickets cost $29 for the coach one way and $49 for the Ferry from Cape Jervis to Kangaroo Island. Kangaroo Island Ferry If you are driving you can take your car on to the Ferry for $98 each way. The Ferry crossing takes roughly 45 minutes.

There are 2 ways to explore the island, you will either need to hire a car(or take your own car over on the ferry) or book a tour as there isn’t any public transport on the Island.

If you choose to hire a car, start your trip to Kangaroo Island by exploring the Islands wildlife. The Island is home to New Zealand Fur Seals at Cape de Couedic, Sea Lions in Seal Bay and Small Penguins at Pennshaw Penguin Centre. You should also keep an eye out for Koala’s and Kangaroo along the way.

If it’s a warm day you can head to a secluded swimming spot like Vivonne Bay or pick a quiet beach like Stokes Bay or Emu Bay to spend the afternoon.

If you’re looking for more active things to do on the Island you can book a Quad bike tour from $147 withKangaroo Island Quad Bike Tours or try some sand boarding and tobogganing from $37 at Little Sahara adventure centre

There are plenty of popular restaurants on the island, Pennshaw Beach and Kingscote both have a collection of Pizzeria’s, fish & chip shops and Australian restaurants.

If you are looking for a package tour that includes the best activities on the island as well as transport you should consider the 2 day tour 2 day Kangaroo Island wild explorer

DAY 4 : Barossa Valley

View Image

DAY 4

Location: Adelaide

Activity: Barossa Valley

The Barossa Valley is a must see whilst in Adelaide. It's one of the most famous Wine regions in the Australia, it’s recommended to spend the day hoping between wineries.

If you have a car you can drive out to the Barossa Valley which is roughly an hour away from ADelaide CBD and stay for the night in one of the boutique hotels. However you will need to book a taxi from your hotel to the wineries as you are likely to be drinking quite a bit at each location and won't be able to drive.

Alternatively you could book a day trip. There are lots to choose from that have very similar itineraries however one example is the Small Group Premium Wine Tour You will stop at 4 different wineries and enjoy some local foods along the way before being dropped back to the accommodation in Adelaide CBD or Glenelg.

Alternatively if you are looking for a slower paced day at the wineries you could opt for the Barossa Valley and Hahndorf Day Tour This tour visits 2 wineries in Barossa Valley as well as stopping at Hahndorf, a small historical town in the Adelaide Hills with little sweet shops and cafes and lots of German History.

Use this website to help narrow down which tour is best for you Amazing Barossa

DAY 6 : Glenelg

View Image

DAY 6

Location: Adelaide

Activity: Glenelg

Glenelg is the main beach town in Adelaide and is located a short 35minute FREE tram ride from the CBD. Glenelg is a long stretch of shallow shores and white sandy beaches and it’s a great spot to relax for the day.

When you arrive you should take a walk along the pier out to sea to get a view of the beach town before picking your spot on the sand for the day.

A popular attraction in Glenelg is the Beachhouse. The beachhouse is the perfect spot to find your inner child, you can go on the bumper cars, bumper boats, arcade games, mini golf or even the water slides just off the main beach.

If the Beachhouse entertainment centre isn’t your thing maybe you’d prefer a lunch date and cocktails on the beach at The Moseley Beach Club where you can lounge on day beds or picnic benches and sip your drink from a coconut.

Make sure you check out Glenelg’s shops on Jetty Road, they have everything from boutique beach clothes to English sweet shops.

DAY 7 : Mount Lofty & Hahndorf

View Image

DAY 7

Location: Adelaide

Activity: Mount Lofty & Hahndorf

Mount Lofty is a lookout point across the whole of Adelaide just a 25 minute drive out of the City.

Mounty Lofty has 8 different walking tracks to the summit ranging from 2 to 4 hours (and back remember!) you can find out more about the walking tracks at Walking SA Alternatively you can drive straight to the summit. There is a car park with pay and display parking and a cafe at the lookout that serves hot food and snacks for breakfast, lunch and dinner.

Keep driving towards Hahndorf which is roughly 15-20 minutes away from the Mount Lofty summit. Hahndorf is a little German town hidden in the Adelaide Hills. Total journey time if driving from Adelaide is 50 minutes, via Mount Lofty or you can catch the 864F bus from Pulteney Street Adelaide (Subject to change so please use google maps) which will take roughly 1 hour.

Despite being a very small town Hahndorf has plenty to do, you can visit Hahndorf Farm Barn and feed the animals, pick Strawberries at Beerenberg Family Farm, visit the German Migration Museum, play a round of mini golf or even just browse the Main Street and try out some of the ale houses.

There are lots of places to eat including Udder Delights Cheese Cellar for an amazing cheese board or Haus for German dishes or pizza’s.

If you don’t have a car to explore and you don’t fancy catching public transport you could opt for a day trip such as 1 Day Adelaide City and Hahndorf Tour. The tour is only 4 hours so you may not get a chance to do everything whilst in Hahndorf or hike at Mount Lofty but if you are strapped for time this is a good alternative to tick it off the bucketlist.

Travel Directions: Adelaide-Melbourne

Location: Adelaide-Melbourne

Activity: Travel

If you have a car you can drive from Adelaide to Melbourne via the famous Great Ocean Road. The total journey is roughly 11 and a half hours. If you have time to spare or if you already planned to visit the Great Ocean Road it’s worth stopping in Warnambool overnight to break up the journey and enjoy a slower drive along the Great Ocean Road the following day. If you’re looking for a shorter journey you can take the inland route which is roughly an 8 hour drive. If you’re on a tight time frame you should fly from Adelaide to Melbourne, it’s a 1 hour and 15 minute flight and can be as cheap as $60 one way. You can also catch a train from Adelaide to Melbourne changing at Nhill from $114. The journey time is roughly 11hours from start to finish.

DAY 8 : Great Ocean Road -The 12 Apostles

View Image

DAY 8

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Great Ocean Road -The 12 Apostles

Hire a car for 2 days to drive the Great Ocean Road. The most savy way to drive the Great ocean Road is actually a little backwards.

Drive inland direct to the 12 apostles. The earlier you can get here the better because there will be lots of coach tours passing through from mid- morning onwards. Most tours only go as far as the 12 Apostles meaning the second half of the route is a lot quieter. Continue North West towards Adelaide as far as Port Fairy which is technically classed the end of the Great Ocean Road, it’s a small town with a few restaurants to stop for dinner. You can stay overnight in Warnanbool which is an area roughly 30 mins before the end of the Great Ocean Road with shops and restaurants and lots of hotels.

The Great Ocean Road has lots of beauty spots along the route so here are the most recommended for this section of the Great Ocean Road.

The 12 apostles- This is the most famous stop on the Great Ocean Road, although there are technically only 8 apostles left. There will be lots of tour coaches arriving here so make sure you get here early.

Gibson steps- A short walk from the 12 apostles, you can walk down to beach on the opposite side of the peninsula at the 12 apostles. The walk will take roughly 30mins each way to get down to the beach.

Loch Ard Gorg.- Another nice view point just 3 minutes West of the 12 Apostles. You can get down to the beach here too if you fancy relaxing on a sunny day.

London Bridge- The next stop just beyond the 12 apostles. It’s a quick stop with lookout platforms over what has been named the London Bridge due to a large section falling down in to the sea.

The Grotto- Roughly 5 minutes beyond London Bridge. The Grotto is a popular spot for taking pictures. It’s roughly a 750m walk from the car park down to the Grotto where you will be able to see through the cave and out to the Ocean. A popular instagrammable stop.

(There are many other stops along this route so you may have more time to explore the rest depending on how long you stop for)

DAY 9 : Great Ocean Road -The Full Drive

View Image

DAY 9

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Great Ocean Road -The Full Drive

Day 2, leave early and get on the road heading back passed the 12 apostles, having covered this already you’ll be able to enjoy the drive straight passed the 12 apostles and on to the next hot spots. You will then be on the road early enough to do the full drive and you will also be driving in the opposite direction to the traffic giving you a little more privacy at each stop and less traffic on the route home.

Wreck Beach(wattlehill)- A good spot to stretch your legs. A secluded beach about a 15min drive on an off road track.(Must have a 4WD) You can either hike up to a look out which can take upto 40mins or take the 375 steps down to the beach. If the tide is low there are 2 anchors visible from shipwrecks that have slowly been washed away over the years.

Cape Otway- A large National Park with lots of hikes to choose from. You can also visit the Lightstation Lightstation for $18.50 and listen to the guide talks as well as walk up to the top of the light house.

Apollo Bay- A coastal Town which is a great place to stop, there are lots of different restaurants, here are trip advisors top 10 Apollo Bay restaurants Whilst in Apollo Bay you can head to the beach for some sun or even book a kayaking tour (90 minutes) to head out looking for fur seals. Apollo Bay Surf & Kayak the tours are $85, or alternatively you could hire some Stand Up paddle boards or take a surf lesson to break up the journey before getting back on the road towards Melbourne.

Grey River road, Kennet River- It’s a short detour off the Great Ocean Road but it’s worth it to spot some Koala’s, as you pull on to the Grey River Road (a short 10 minute detour off of the Great Ocean Road) keep your eyes peeled for the Koala’s that live here.

Eastern View- The start of the great ocean road and where you will find The memorial Arch sign. A very quick photo stop to get a picture with the Great Ocean Road sign. From here it is roughly 2 hours back to Melbourne CBD.

There are a few other popular beach towns on the drive back to Melbourne such as Lorne, Torquay and Bells Beach which are also other possible stops for lunch and dinner depending on the time you have.

DAY 10 : Melbourne Zoo

View Image

DAY 10

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Melbourne Zoo

The Melbourne Zoo is open every day from 09:00 – 17:00. Trains run to Royal Park Station on the Upfield Line. Take Tram 55 which runs from William St in the city and stops in front of the zoo. Tickets are $38 and can be purchased online or on the day. You can also book up close experiences with Gorilla’s, Giraffe’s and even the Tigers.

The Zoo has 3 cafe’s onsite so you can enjoy, The Lakeside Cafe, the Elephant Cafe and the Giraffe Lookout Cafe.

DAY 11 : The Art Scene

View Image

DAY 11

Location: Melbourne

Activity: The Art Scene

Melbourne is known as one of the world’s great street art capitals for its unique expressions of art displayed on approved outdoor locations throughout the city. Here are a few streets featuring great works; Hosier and Rutledge Lane, opposite Federation Square, Caledonian Lane, off Little Bourke Street, Union Lane, off Bourke Street Mall, Rear of 280 Queen Street in Finlay Avenue, 21 Degraves Street, Corner of Flinders Lane and Cocker Alley , 122 Palmerston Street, Carlton.

The area out near the Rose Street Artists Market is another great area. It isn’t just street art that Melbourne has to offer. Visit the National Gallery of Victoria (NGV) located over the bridge from Federation Square pass the Arts Centre. Houses an extensive collection from Europe, Asia, America, and Oceania. General entry is free and the gallery is open 10:00 – 17:00 every day.

The Ian Potter Centre located in Federation Square houses Australian art, presenting Indigenous and non-Indigenous art from the colonial period to the present day. General entry is free and the gallery is open 10:00 – 17:00.

DAY 12 : St Kilda

View Image

DAY 12

Location: Melbourne

Activity: St Kilda

Take the tram to St Kilda to visit Melbourne’s closest beach (Very different to the beaches on the East Coast). The quickest way to get there is the Tram, take the 96 from Bourke Street towards St Kilda. St. Kilda is a beachside destination about a 20 minute tram ride away. If it's a warm day head to Stand Up Paddle Board HQ to hire a SUP. You can hire a board for $30 for an hour between 9am and 1pm. Stand Up Paddle Board HQ

Whilst your here check out Luna Park!

Luna Park is an old carnival style theme park at St. Kilda. It is generally open on the weekends and is free to enter. A ride costs $10.95 or you can buy unlimited rides for $47.50.

Acland Street is a street in the Melbourne suburb of St Kilda, which enjoys great popularity as a recreational area, mainly due to its many restaurants and its proximity to the entertainment areas along St Kilda beach. Have a wine at The Vineyard or have a coffee and cheesecake at Monarch Cakes. Down by the beach is a cool bar Republica that has a great menu.

Take the Tram 16 back to the city (as opposed to the 96). This way you will travel along St. Kilda Rd and have an opportunity to jump off at the Shrine of Remembrance, Victoria’s memorial to the men and women who have served Australia in armed conflicts and peace keeping missions. The Shrine is open 10:00 – 17:00 every day. You could also wander through a section of the Botanic Gardens as you take the 1.3 km walk back to Federation Square.

DAY 13 : Shop till you drop!

View Image

DAY 13

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Shop till you drop!

Melbourne's retail heart on Bourke St Mall links Swanston and Elizabeth streets and is only open to trams and pedestrians. Listen out for the bells of approaching trams as you drift between department stores and the flagship stores. Along Bourke St you’ll also find Australia’s two main department stores, Myer & David Jones. Melbourne’s GPO from 1854 is a multi-level shopping complex featuring H&M and similar stores. A short walk away is Emporium, with upmarket retailers and a great food court.

For both a cultural and shopping experience head to The Queen Victoria Market. Spread over several city blocks with over 600 retailers the market is a reflection of Melbourne’s cosmopolitan make-up. Fruit, vegetables, local and imported goods, fashion and souvenirs. Warm up in the winter months with a hot jam donut and a coffee. Listen to the butchers advertise their specials and sample some artisan cheese and breads. The market is closed on Mondays. The left hand column is the fresh produce section and the right hand column is the specialty shopping section.

The Market is only a 7 minute walk from Melbourne Central Station (along Elizabeth Street) and Flagstaff Station (along William Street). The market is also accessible with the free City Circle Tram.

For an awesome off-the-beaten-track market head out to the Rose Street Artist’s Market where emerging artists and designers showcase their work over the weekend. Check out quirky furniture, fashion, intricate jewellery, paintings and postcards. 60 Rose St Fitzroy, in between Brunswick and Nicholson Streets. Sat – Sun 11:00 – 17:00.

From the city catch tram 96 from Bourke St (get off at stop 16) or 11 from Collins St. (get off at stop 17). The trip takes about 15 minutes. Prahan Market is known as the ‘Food Lover’s Market’. Take Tram no.72 to Camberwell rom Swanston Street. Jump off at stop no. 30 outside of the market. The market is open Tues, Thurs, Fri, Sat 07:00 – 17:00. The market is open 10:00 – 15:00.

DAY 14 : Melbourne SEALife Aquarium

DAY 15 : Special Interest Museums

View Image

DAY 15

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Special Interest Museums

A multicultural city with influences from all over world adding to the melting pot that is Melbourne.

The Immigration Museum is a museum primarily displaying Australia's immigration history. It is located on Flinders Street in Melbourne, Victoria, in the Old Customs House. Accessible on Free Tram or a short walk from Flinders Street or Southern Cross Stations. Entry is just $14.00 and the museum is open from 10:00am – 17:00pm.

Melbourne Museum showcases Australian social history, indigenous cultures, science and the environment. It is a nice walk from the City where you can check out the Carlton Gardens and Exhibition Building. It is also home to IMAX Theatre. Opening times are 10:00am – 17:00pm and entry is $15.00. IMAX tickets start from $15.00.

One of Australia’s most iconic figures was the bushranger Ned Kelly. Villain or hero, his story has lived on since his death at the Old Melbourne Gaol in 1880. The gaol runs various night tours including a ghost tour.

To see the original armour Ned Kelly wore in his last stand against the police you can visit the State Library of Victoria, opposite Melbourne Central Station. Visit between 10:00am and 17:00pm.

DAY 19 : Philip Island Day Trip

View Image

DAY 19

Location: Melbourne

Activity: Philip Island Day Trip

Philip Island Day trip is the best place to see Melbourne’s Fairy Penguins. A day tour will give you access to the wildlife park and also let you see the thousands of penguins come out of the ocean at dusk to sleep under the rocks on the beach. Philip Island Tour

Philip Island is just a 90 minute drive south of Melbourne City. The Island is full of wildlife and you’ll be able to get up close with Koala’s, wombats and Dingos as well as catch the world famous Penguin parade. The Penguin Parade happens at dusk when around 4000 tiny penguin come out of the sea and walk to their little homes within the rocks for the night. You can either make your own way to Philip Island and book on to a penguin parade tour or you can take a day trip that will pick you up from Melbourne. The day trips are all day so it’s worth taking a few snacks for the journey etc however there will be opportunities to grab some food along the way.

Location: Melbourne-Canberra

Activity: Travel

If you have a car you can drive from Melbourne to Canberra via the M31. The total journey is roughly 7 hours.

If your’e using public transport you can catch a train from Southern Cross Station to Jolimont Tourist Centre in Canberra changing at Wodonga. Total journey time is just under 9 hours and train prices cost between $70-$200 depending on when you are travelling.

DAY 24 : Walk around the City

View Image

DAY 24

Location: Canberra

Activity: Walk around the City

When you first arrive in Canberra you will want to explore the City and see the landmarks. Start the tour by exploring the London Circuit and Canberra Centre, checking out the shops and coffee spots you’ll be trying later.

Once you’ve finished browsing the shops head towards the Australian War Memorial.

You must have ticket to enter the War Memorial, they are free to book online, you just need to register for a particular time slot to avoid overcrowding. You may be able to get tickets at the gate however it is subject to availability. Tickets allow you from 1-2hours access.

Next up take a walk along Anzac Parade towards Commonwealth park and enjoy the view of Lake Burley Griffin. Cross the Waterloo memorial bridge and walk towards Capital Hill. This walk should take around 1 hour.

Capital Hill is home to Parliament House and Embassy’s from all over the world as well as Australia’s National Portrait Gallery. The gallery is free to enter however you may be required to book a time slot online before arriving so they can manage capacity. Opening times are between 10am and 5pm.

Spend the rest of the afternoon exploring the art work before making your way towards Kingston Foreshore which is around a 30 minute walk.

There are plenty of restaurant choices including Sammy’s@Foreshore for Chinese or Walt & Burley’s Gastropub or just head to Thirty8 Espresso for cocktails on the river.

DAY 25 : Mount Ainslie Lookout

View Image

DAY 25

Location: Canberra

Activity: Mount Ainslie Lookout

The walk to the Mount Ainslie Lookout will take between 1.5-2hours from the War Memorial. Head towards the Australian Defence Force Academy on Fairbairn Avenue before turning left onto Mount Ainslie Drive. The walk up to the top is around 3km from here.

Once you are at the lookout point you will have a view of the whole City looking straight down Anzac Parade from above. The view is worth the walk however you can also drive straight up to the lookout if your prefer to save yourself the walk.

Alternatively if you fancy a more relaxed walk you can visit the Australian National Botanical Gardens to see the largest Flora display in Australia. You can stop for a coffee and a snack at Pollen which is set within the Gardens.

If you are travelling during the summer months you can book yourself a seat at Sunset Cinema set within the Australian National Botanical Gardens. Tickets can be purchased online at https://www.sunsetcinema.com.au/canberra/ between November and March. Food and drinks stands are onsite or you can pack your own picnic.

DAY 26 : Lake Burley Griffin Hike

View Image

DAY 26

Location: Canberra

Activity: Lake Burley Griffin Hike

The Lake Burley Griffin loop is a total of 29km and covers all three sections of the Lake. If you are looking to cover the full route you will need a full day and it can take anywhere between 6-8hours depending on your pace.

If you’re looking to do a shorter route it’s recommended to cover the centre basin (the middle section) as this covers the most landmarks along the walk and helps you find your bearings in the City. This section of the Lake is just a 5km loop and should take between 1.5-2hours.

The Australian Government site provides a self guided walking tour map to help highlight the landmarks during this walk and can be downloaded here file:///Users/mariareynolds/Downloads/Lake%20Burley%20Griffin_WalkingTour_Flyer%202019_online.pdf

End the day by heading to London Circuit, which is a great spot for pubs, bars and restaurants.

Try Kokomos for a trendy vibe and lively atmosphere with a Tiki cocktail theme and street food bar, bar snacks and burgers or Sage Farm and Mint for a sophisticated sit down dinner. King O’Malley’s is the spot for Live music and bistro food in a classic Irish pub or finally Mooseheads pub and Nightclub is a great spot to end the night as one of Canberra’s busiest night spots.

DAY 27 : Huskissons Bay

View Image

DAY 27

Location: Jervis Bay

Activity: Huskissons Bay

Jervis Bay is a coastal town around 3 hours South of Sydney. The best place to stay is Huskissons Bay as it offers the most shops and restaurants. The majority of the surrounding is either a National park or secluded beach. The best part about Jervis Bay is the fact its so private, the beaches offer lots of space and are rarely busy, even on public holidays.

The beach is a peninsula so you have to drive back out of town and around to the peninsula. There are very little waves in the harbour which means it’s a great place to paddle board or kayak. In the afternoon head out to one of the many recommended hidden beaches in the area, for example Honeymoon Bay, Greenfield Beach or Green Patch. Honeymoon Bay offers a very narrow stretch of beach but it’s a great place to relax as the bay has almost no waves meaning you can relax in the waste height waters or go a little further out for some snorkelling.

DAY 28 : Beach Day- Worlds whitest beach

View Image

DAY 28

Location: Jervis Bay

Activity: Beach Day- Worlds whitest beach

Head straight to Hyams beach for the day. This is the Guiness Book of Records whitest beach in the world! The sand is so incredibly clean and white that it actually sqeaks as you walk across it. Hyams beach is almost 3km long so you will have lots of privacy. The waves here are pretty high and you can hear them crashing before you see the beach.

DAY 29 : The Cove

View Image

DAY 29

Location: The Cove

Activity: The Cove

Arrive at The Cove for day 1 off the grid. In order to get to The Cove you will be driving through the National Park, which means you may be required to pay the National Park fee which is $13per vehicle. The roads are extremely uneven and it is recommended to have a car that isn’t too low to the ground and preferably a 4WD. This road continues for nearly 30 minutes and you’ll be sure you are lost before finally arriving at the the beautiful Cove.

From the moment you arrive you will want to be snapping pictures of everything. You’ll have kangaroo’s hopping passed you and possums and Kookaburra’s spying you from the tree’s.

From here it’s time to unwind, take a bath, sit by the fire, unpack the picnic and relax.

Book out a kayak or stand up paddle board for a couple of hours in the afternoon and paddle upstream towards…. Where you’ll find a little fish and chip shop. Take a quick stop for some food on the banks before heading back for more relaxing in the evening.

The Cove has BBQ’s, Pizza ovens so you can cook up a storm in one of the many chill out spots before settling in by the fire pits with some friendly kangaroos and some marshmallows.

DAY 30 : The Cove

View Image

Location: The Cove

Activity: The Cove

Get up early for sunrise and take a walk along the beach front, it’s completely private and you’re likely to be one of the only people there. Enjoy the beach walk and maybe even head in for a swim if the water look inviting.

DAY 33 : Spit to Manly Coastal Walk

View Image

DAY 33

Location: Sydney

Activity: Spit to Manly Coastal Walk

The walk takes between 2.5-3hours and the terrain is overall pretty flat with a hand full of small inclines. You can take either the 178 or 180 bus from Wynyard station (check this using google maps before you leave as alternate bus routes may be available depending on the time of day) to Spit West Reserve I.e the start of the Spit bridge. The coastal walk starts on the seaboard side of the bridge.(walk across the bridge and the path is on the left hand side. It’s a fairly easy walk but wear walking shoes as it’s 10km. Also make sure you take plenty of water as there is only 1 cafe along the path, around 30-45mins from the start. The walk has lots of beautiful beaches and view points across the harbour.

At the end of the walk you will arrive at Manly Wharf. I recommend either the Manly Hotel or the Manly Skiff for lunch. Both are on the waterfront and have good food/cocktails. If you’re looking for something cheaper try Betty’s Burgers at the Ferry terminal. Spend the afternoon at the Manly Main beach (This is not the beach you see when you first arrive, it’s a few minutes walk) or shop along the highstreet. There are loads of great bikini stores here.

Take the Ferry from Manly wharf back to Circular Quay. If you go on a Sunday travel is capped at $2.80. Ferry takes around 30minutes.

DAY 39 : Jet Boating on Sydney Harbour

View Image

DAY 39

Location: Sydney

Activity: Jet Boating on Sydney Harbour

Jet Boating is not just an extreme Watersport, it’s also a great way to see Sydney Harbour. There are a few different companies that run Jet boats on the harbour, standard prices across the companies is $85pp however they often offer discounts up to 40% off so check all the companies for the best rates.

Jet boats are designed to glide along the top of the water at high speed. You’ll be doing 360 degree spins up and down the harbour dodging landmarks.

Once you finished exploring Sydney Harbour head to the Rocks markets. The markets are open Friday-Sunday until 5pm. The Rocks has some of the oldest pubs in Sydney amongst the upmarket restaurants and street food stools, this is why it’s such a popular spot, It has something for everyone.

DAY 47 : Sydney Museums

View Image

DAY 47

Location: Sydney

Activity: Sydney Museums

The Museum of Sydney shows you how Sydney has changed over the years. The Sydney Museum is a modern museum built over and around the remains of Australia’s first Government House. The Museum of Sydney celebrates the people and events that have shaped the character and soul of this city. $15.00. Open Daily 10:00 – 17:00. The Museum is on the corner of Philip & Bridge Street.

Learn about how the convicts lived in the World Heritage listed Hyde Park Barracksh. A fascinating look into transportation and a nation built on a convict past. Modern Sydney is built on convict foundations – on convict labour, skills and stories. 50,000 convicts passed through its gates. Entrance is free however if you want an audio tour there is an additional cost. Opening times are 10:00 – 17:00 everyday.

Each year, Australians nation-wide commemorate Anzac Day on 25 April. The Anzac Memorial , located a few minute walk from our hotel in Hyde Park, is a place of commemoration and remembrance of the service and sacrifice of Australian men and women in war and peacekeeping activities since 1914.  The Memorial is open every day from 09.00 to 17:00. Entry to the Memorial is free of charge, though donations are welcome.

The Australian Museum is in Hyde Park. The museum shows you Australia over time, dinosaurs and their relatives , Earth Science and much more. The Australian Museum is open 09.30 to 17:00. Tickets cost $15.00 for the permanent exhibition and $23.00 if you also want to visit the popup exhibitions.

At the Maritime Museum you can climb aboard real-life tall ships, warships and a submarine and explore temporary exhibitions all centred on Australia and it’s relationship with the sea. The Museum is open 09:00 – 17:00 with last boarding time for vessels being 16:10. Located on Darling Harbour (The Prymont Side), the museum is a 25 minute walk from Town Hall. You can take A Ferry from Circular Quay or walk in 30 mins. A Big Ticket costs $25.00 and includes access to everything.

DAY 49 : Explore The Blue Mountains

View Image

DAY 49

Location: The Blue Mountains

Activity: Explore The Blue Mountains

Catching sunrise in the Blue Mountains is a must and the best way to do this is to head to one of the Blue Mountains lookout points that don’t require any hiking, such as The Three Sisters Rocks. The Three Sister are a popular tourist spot and are often very busy with tour companies so if you’re going to see it, it’s probably best to come for sunrise before the crowds turn up.

From here head to Wentworth Falls for a short hike, roughly 45 minutes to an hour. The hike is Grade 3 which means you must be wearing suitable footwear etc however it should require above normal fitness. You can find out a little more about this hike here https://www.nationalparks.nsw.gov.au/things-to-do/walking-tracks/wentworth-falls-track

Now you’ve earnt yourself a nice lunch so head towards Leura to check out some of the village cafes and shops. The Red Door cafe is a great spot for breakfast and lunch and they serve a great coffee, however many of the little breakfast/lunch spots along the high street are great.

If you’re looking for a seat with a view head to Solitary which is in Katoomba, the outdoor seating area has a view over the Jamison Valley and you’ll be able to chose from an extensive menu.

In the afternoon check out a few more lookout spots that don’t require any hiking such as Lincoln Rock (near Wentworth Falls so may be worth doing this at the same time, depending how hungry you are before lunch!) Blackheath Lookout and Pulpit Rock Lookout.

DAY 50 : Grand Canyon Hike

DAY 50

The Grand Canyon Hike is one of the longer of the Blue Mountains but it’s definitely a favourite. You will drive straight to Evans Lookout in Blackheath which gives you an idea of the kind of views you can expect on this hike.

From Evans Lookout car park you will see the sign posts for the Grand Canyon Walk, this route is a 6km loop and will take roughly 3 hours however you should allow a little more time for stopping and of course taking lots of pictures.

DAY 51 : Jenolan Caves

View Image

DAY 51

Location: The Blue Mountains

Activity: Jenolan Caves

The Jenolan Caves are nestled into the Blue Mountains, they are roughly 90 minutes from Leura which is one of the main accommodation hubs.

There are 15 different cave tours run by https://www.jenolancaves.org.au/ that cover the best of the Jenolan Caves. Group sizes are up to 35 people and prices range from $42-55 per adult for standard packages. Most tours last for 90 minutes meaning you can do more than 1 if you can’t decide which tour to pick.

Each cave offers a different experience so have a look at the details of each before you book, you can also see pictures of each cave which should help you make a decision.

If your not looking to book a tour there is one cave that is open for free to the public. Nettle Cave is an open air cave meaning it is slightly different to the others and therefore has a different shape and style however it’s a great option for a passing visit or to tick it off the bucket list on a budget.

Visit Caves House Hotel for lunch or dinner at Chisolm’s restaurant. They have one of few large dining halls left in the area and they offer an a la carte menu. Shoal Bay is located a 1 hour drive North of Newcastle in Port Stephens. Port Stephens is a collection of 26 beautiful beaches overlooking the Karuah River. Shoal Bay can be found on the Peninsula of Tomaree National Park.

Shoal Bay is just one of the many spots to stop in Port Stephens however it is highly recommended due to the National Park surrounding it. Tomaree Mountain is set on the tip of the Peninsula and offers views over Shoal Bay and Port Stephens.

DAY 55 : The Central Coast- Terrigal and Avoca

View Image

DAY 55

Location: The Central Coast- Terrigal and Avoca

Activity: The Central Coast- Terrigal and Avoca

The Central Coast is just 1 hour North of Sydney and is the start of the North Coast. You can get here by train, bus or car from Sydney.

The first place on your list should be Terrigal, a little coastal town with white beaches that are much quieter than what you will find in Sydney. Terrigal beach is a beauty and it’s surrounded by restaurants so you don’t need to go far after spending a day at the beach.

Just outside of Terrigal you’ll find the famous Avoca beach, a popular spot and often rated in the top 10 beaches on the Northern Coast. Avoca is slightly smaller with fewer eateries however Becker and Co does a great breakfast/lunch menu with unique tastes such as the ham and pineapple toasties, not one for the Hawaiian haters out there. They have other great options and fancy coffees too.

Avoca Beach is the best of both world due to the sand dunes that have broken the ocean from an estuary, creating a lake right next to the ocean. The water is really shallow and therefore super warm during summer and also very calm which gives you another option as the waves in the Ocean can be quite strong.

Other favourites in the area are McMasters Beach, Copacabana and Umina Beach

DAY 56 : The Central Coast- Caves Beach and Newcastle

View Image

DAY 56

Location: The Central Coast- Caves Beach and Newcastle

Activity: The Central Coast- Caves Beach and Newcastle

Caves Beach is located just south of Newcastle and it’s a must stop on your journey. The name says it all, Caves beach is full of hidden caves that take you to hidden beaches.

A big mistake some travellers make is visiting at high tide making it extremely difficult and dangerous to enter the caves and is not advised. Check out the best time for low tide and make your way to the South end of the beach to Sea Cave. You should see an opening in to the cave just across the rocks, as long as the tide is heading out you should be able to walk through the cave and find the little tunnels they take you out to an otherwise unaccessible beach on the other side of the point.

Please take extra care when visiting and make sure you are sure about the tide times as you do not want to end up stuck on the wrong side of the cave!

After an adventurous beach day keeping heading North on your journey towards Newcastle.

Once you have settled in Newcastle head to the Honeysuckle Hotel for an Espresso Martini with an atmosphere.

Travel Directions: Sydney-Byron

Location: Sydney-Byron

Activity: Travel

Greyhound buses which run twice a day take 12 and a half hours. Average price is $100-175 again depending on what day/season you are travelling.

DAY 60 : Sunrise at the Lighthouse and Surf lesson

View Image

DAY 60

Location: Byron Bay

Activity: Sunrise at the Lighthouse and Surf lesson

Set your alarm clock for EARLY! (Google sunrise, roughly 5:30am). Head up to the Lighthouse for sunrise, it's so worth the morning hike for a chance to see this view. Byron Bay Lighthouse is located at Cape Byron, the most Easterly point of Australia. From the top you are likely to see all kinds of sea life, such as Turtles, Dolphins and even Whales passing by from up here.

Book a surf lesson at Lennox head with Mojo Surf . If you head to Mojo Surf on Fletcher street they can book you in for a morning or afternoon session running at either 8:30am or 12:30pm. Lennox head has a huge stretch of beach and perfect conditions for learning to surf. The lessons are around 3-4 hours so you'll be finishing around lunch time but before heading back to Byron you need to check out Lake Ainsworth just off of the beach and carpark.

Lake Ainsworth is a tea tree lake which essentially means the oils from the surrounding tea trees seep in to the lake turning the water so dark it's almost impossible to clearly see your own hands under the water. The effects of this however means your hair and skin feel smooth and silky even after stepping out of the salty sea. The water is so warm it's almost like bath water. It's a beautiful place to relax until sunset with some lilo's and a few drinks before heading off to the next spot on your east coast adventure.

Round off the day at main beach before heading to Cheeky Monkeys for a night of super cheap happy hour drinks and dancing on tables!

Tip: Check their websites as they often have theme nights or quiz nights. We managed to win the quiz and got some free surfing lessons which was a perfect plan for the rest of our stay.

DAY 61 : Waterfalls

View Image

DAY 61

Location: Byron Bay

Activity: Waterfalls

Head out to Killen Falls, it's around a half an hour drive and then just a 10 minute walk to the waterfall. Make sure you are in comfortable shoes as it can be a little slippery. The waterfall sits over a cave meaning you can walk behind it or set up in the shade whilst you're swimming beneath the waterfall.

The second stop is Minyon Falls. Minyon falls is a 45 minute drive North of Killen falls in Nightcap National Park. The waterfall itself is 100m and you can take an 8km circuit to see the top and bottom of the waterfall. However one thing to take in to consideration is the weather, If you take the 40 minute drive on a nice hot day in the middle of summer you may find one very dried out waterfall. Which could be a little frustrating, however at the top of the waterfall there were a few pockets of water that are deep enough to use as plunge pools overlooking the national park that don't should still be full.

You must stay away from the edge at the top of the waterfall as the rocks can be slippery and this could be extremely dangerous

.

DAY 64 : Whale Watching Tour

DAY 64

Location: Gold Coast

Activity: Whale Watching Tour

Whales migrate up and down the East coast of Australia along the coastline and the Gold Coast is a perfect place to spot them. Book a Sea World tour Sea World tour to catch a close up glimpse of the whales. Tours depart 3 times a day and run for 2 and a half hours. The boats have 3 decks and an onboard bar for refreshments. In the unlikely case that you are unable to see any Whales you will get a free return ticket.(Recommend doing this on one of your first days on the Gold Coast incase you do need to rebook)

Once you’re back on land and beaming from your day at sea, book a table at Four Winds 360 restaurant. Four Winds is a 360 revolving restaurant that offers buffet lunches and dinners starting from $65 with an ever changing view.

DAY 66 : Surfers Paradise- SkyPoint

View Image

DAY 66

Location: Surfers Paradise

Activity: Surfers Paradise- SkyPoint

Head to Australia’s only beachside Observation Deck and the tallest residential building in the world. You can go up to the 77th floor and see the 360 degree view of Surfers Paradise. Tickets are $27pp for entry to the skydeck where you will get a view of the city and the beach.

You can also eat at the Skypoint Bistro + Bar , they have an Australian menu with gluten free and vegan options as well as afternoon tea for two.

Tickets start at a really reasonable $77pp for a day time climb, however for $87pp you will receive a $20 food voucher the the sky point bistro so you can enjoy lunch with a view after working up an appetite.

Surfers Paradise is definitely your place for night life. You’ll find lots of clubs to party all night on Orchid Avenue. Most of these clubs have an entry fee of $10-20 and drinks can be quite expensive but you will notice club reps outside most of these places and you’ll be able to ask around to find the best deals.

DAY 72 : Mount Coot-tha

View Image

DAY 72

Location: Brisbane

Activity: Mount Coot-tha

Mount Coot-tha is just inland of Brisbane and is a great place to visit to get out of the City for the day and enjoy the epic views. You can catch public transport from Central station to the Mount Coot-tha Lookout however this will involve 3 bus changes and takes roughly an hour. Alternatively you can catch a train from central to Toowong station and get an Uber to drop you at the start of the JC Slaughter Falls picnic area.

Mount Coot-ha has its own shuttle bus service that you can hop on and off between these stops:

* Sir Samuel Griffith Drive - Mt Coot-tha Car Park

* Sir Samuel Griffith Drive - Mahogany Trail

* Sir Samuel Griffith Drive - J. C. Slaughter Falls Picnic Area

* Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mt Coot-tha (also Sir Thomas Brisbane Planetarium, Mt Coot-tha Library and Mt Coot-tha Visitor Information Centre).

The shuttle runs as follows:

summer (1 October to 30 April) - 8.40am-7pm

winter (1 May to 30 September) - 9.40am-4.40pm.

Mount Coot-the Loop is a 10km hiking trail around Mount Coot-tha that is great for hiking, running or cycling. DAY 75 : Hiking

View Image

DAY 75

Location: Glass House Mountains

Activity: Hiking

There are lots of different mountains to climb here so make sure you check the difficulty of each mountain before you decide which one is best for you. Make sure you have everything you need before you set off, including water and suitable shoes. DO NOT do any of these in flip flops (thongs) because even one of the easiest mountains will be impossible.

The below website has some great information about the different walking tracks and the difficulty levels of each of the mountains.

Glass House Mountains

One example is Mount Beerburrum which is one of the less extreme mountains to climb, although it is still extremely steep, it is one of the shorter climbs. We recommend getting to the top in time for sunset as the views are incredible, start the climb at least an hour before sunset to allow you plenty of time to get to the top.

Before you set off make sure you check mountain closures online as currently some of the mountains are closed for resurfacing.

The Glass House Mountains are easily accessed on the train from Brisbane towards Noosa or vice versa. Mount Beerburrum is an convenient option because you can get off the train at Beerburrum station and it's around a 10 minute walk to the bottom of the mountain. the trains come every 1-1.5hours so make sure you time the trains that you plan to catch to continue your journey as there isn't anywhere else to go around the station. If you are travelling with suitcases I wouldn't recommend doing the hike unless you have accomodation to leave your belongings at.

DAY 76 : Animal Encounters

View Image

DAY 76

Location: Australia Zoo

Activity: Animal Encounters

Australia Zoo belongs to the famous Irwin family. It’s an East Coast ‘MUST DO’ so make sure it’s on your bucket list. You can get a free shuttle from Beerwah station that takes you straight to the Zoo or take a public bus, as many routes go to the Zoo directly. The opening times are 9am-5pm daily including weekends and school holidays, however these are naturally a lot busier. One of the perks of visiting during the school holidays, the Zoo hosts lots of extra seasonal activities and you are likely to see the Irwins themselves hosting crocodile feeding shows, Tigers talks and more.

An adult admission ticket is $59 and a childs' ticket is $35, you can also purchase annual passes meaning you'll save money if you plan to visit the zoo more than once.

If you're looking to get a bit closer to the animals the Zoo offers lots of different encounters meaning you can cuddle up to Tiger cubs, lemurs or get yourself an infamous koala selfie.

DAY 79 : National Park Coastal Walk

View Image

DAY 79

Location: Noosa

Activity: National Park Coastal Walk

Visit Noosa's National Park and join one of the many walking tracks.

If you’re looking for scenic views and hidden beaches take the Coastal walk. Make sure you take some water and snacks for an afternoon at one of the beach stops.

The Noosa Fairy Pools are hidden half way along the National Park Coastal track, if you’re wearing sturdy footwear you can walk along the rocks to the Fairy Pools that are often empty. If you check the tide times and the tide is low you can head in for a swim whilst the waves crash in. Be super careful and stay away from the edges in particular on the right hand side. This spot can be dangerous if you are not careful, large freak waves can occasionally crash against the right side and you could be knocked in so please stay clear of any wet rocks or the edge of the rocks. If you plan to swim stick to the central path that takes you down to the narrowest part of the Fairy Pool as seen in the picture.

DAY 90 : White water rafting

View Image

DAY 90

Location: Cairns

Activity: White water rafting

One of the most popular activities in Cairns is White Water Rafting. Book a half day tour with Foaming Fury and spend 2 full hours rafting along Barron river. You will be picked up from Cairns and driven 20 minutes to the Barron River where you will be given your equipment and taught some of the things you’ll need to know on the river. The Barron River has grade 3 rapids which is suitable for beginners. Prices start from $145.

If you like the sound of White water rafting but you’re on a tighter budget you could book a river tubing trip on the Mulgrave river for $90. Again you will be picked up from Cairns and dropped back again. This experience will be roughly 4 and a half hours.

You will need to take a towel, a change of clothes, suncream and some water.

You’ve worked up an appetite so treat yourself to a nice dinner at the Salt House which offers one of the best seats in town. Right on the marina, they serve lunch and dinner and you can choose from the Bar, restaurant or pizzeria. This is the go-to for locals as it’s such a great location.
